body:
**Constants must have upper case names** but

If `const` has the same type as function argument ([Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=903792ee9bfc62ed24576bc4670511ee))
```rust
const value: &str = "";

fn to_owned(value: &str) -> String {
    value.to_string()
}

fn main() {
    to_owned("hello");
}
```
compiler gives error
```
error[E0005]: refutable pattern in function argument: `&_` not covered
 --> src/main.rs:3:13
  |
3 | fn to_owned(value: &str) -> String {
  |             ^^^^^ interpreted as a constant pattern, not new variable
```
but if `const` has another type ([Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=064fbaa9de7afef4a8f91b63350e7f08))
```rust
const value: u8 = 0;

fn to_owned(value: &str) -> String {
    value.to_string()
}

fn main() {
    to_owned("hello");
}
```
error will be
```
error[E0308]: mismatched types
 --> src/main.rs:3:13
  |
3 | fn to_owned(value: &str) -> String {
  |             ^^^^^ expected &str, found u8
  |
  = note: expected type `&str`
             found type `u8`
```
which is as much incomprehensible as possible, especially for people who don't know about const patterns in argument position.
